# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: node-link-diagrams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] An **influence diagram** (**ID**) (also called a **relevance diagram**, **decision diagram** or a **decision network**) is a compact graphical and mathematical representation of a decision situation.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] It is a generalization of a Bayesian network, in which not only probabilistic inference problems but also decision making problems (following the maximum expected utility criterion) can be modeled and solved.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] ID was first developed in the mid-1970s by decision analysts with an intuitive semantic that is easy to understand.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] It is now adopted widely and becoming an alternative to the decision tree which typically suffers from exponential growth in number of branches with each variable modeled.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] ID is directly applicable in team decision analysis, since it allows incomplete sharing of information among team members to be modeled and solved explicitly.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Extensions of ID also find their use in game theory as an alternative representation of the game tree.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] An ID is a directed acyclic graph with three types (plus one subtype) of node and three types of arc (or arrow) between nodes.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Formally, the semantic of influence diagram is based on sequential construction of nodes and arcs, which implies a specification of all conditional independencies in the diagram.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] The specification is defined by the d -separation criterion of Bayesian network.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] According to this semantic, every node is probabilistically independent on its non-successor nodes given the outcome of its immediate predecessor nodes.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Likewise, a missing arc between non-value node X and non-value node Y implies that there exists a set of non-value nodes Z , e.g., the parents of Y , that renders Y independent of X given the outcome of the nodes in Z .
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Consider the simple influence diagram representing a situation where a decision-maker is planning their vacation.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] The above example highlights the power of the influence diagram in representing an extremely important concept in decision analysis known as the value of information.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Scenario 1 is the best possible scenario for this decision situation since there is no longer any uncertainty on what they care about (*Weather Condition*) when making their decision.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Scenario 3, however, is the worst possible scenario for this decision situation since they need to make their decision without any hint (*Weather Forecast*) on what they care about (*Weather Condition*) will turn out to be.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] The decision-maker is usually better off (definitely no worse off, on average) to move from scenario 3 to scenario 2 through the acquisition of new information.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] The most they should be willing to pay for such move is called the value of information on *Weather Forecast*, which is essentially the value of imperfect information on *Weather Condition*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] The applicability of this simple ID and the value of information concept is tremendous, especially in medical decision making when most decisions have to be made with imperfect information about their patients, diseases, etc.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] Influence diagrams are hierarchical and can be defined either in terms of their structure or in greater detail in terms of the functional and numerical relation between diagram elements.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] An ID that is consistently defined at all levels—structure, function, and number—is a well-defined mathematical representation and is referred to as a *well-formed influence diagram* (WFID).
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] WFIDs can be evaluated using reversal and removal operations to yield answers to a large class of probabilistic, inferential, and decision questions.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] More recent techniques have been developed by artificial intelligence researchers concerning Bayesian network inference (belief propagation).
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] An influence diagram having only uncertainty nodes (i.e., a Bayesian network) is also called a **relevance diagram**.
[src:node-link-diagrams/influence-diagram] An arc connecting node *A* to *B* implies not only that "*A* is relevant to *B*", but also that "*B* is relevant to *A*" (i.e., relevance is a symmetric relationship).
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] The ideal form for a layered drawing would be an upward planar drawing, in which all edges are oriented in a consistent direction and no pairs of edges cross.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] In its simplest form, layered graph drawing algorithms may require O(*mn*) time in graphs with *n* vertices and *m* edges, because of the large number of dummy vertices that may be created.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] However, for some variants of the algorithm, it is possible to simulate the effect of the dummy vertices without actually constructing them explicitly, leading to a near-linear time implementation.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] The "dot" tool in Graphviz produces layered drawings.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] A layered graph drawing algorithm is also included in Microsoft Automatic Graph Layout and in Tulip.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] Although typically drawn with vertices in rows and edges proceeding from top to bottom, layered graph drawing algorithms may instead be drawn with vertices in columns and edges proceeding from left to right.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] The same algorithmic framework has also been applied to radial layouts in which the graphs are arranged in concentric circles around some starting node and to three-dimensional layered drawings of graphs.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] In layered graph drawings with many long edges, edge clutter may be reduced by grouping sets of edges into bundles and routing them together through the same set of dummy vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] Similarly, for drawings with many edges crossing between pairs of consecutive layers, the edges in maximal bipartite subgraphs may be grouped into confluent bundles.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] Drawings in which the vertices are arranged in layers may be constructed by algorithms that do not follow Sugiyama's framework.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] For instance, it is possible to tell whether an undirected graph has a drawing with at most *k* crossings, using *h* layers, in an amount of time that is polynomial for any fixed choice of *k* and *h*, using the fact that the graphs that have drawings of this type have bounded pathwidth.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] For layered drawings of concept lattices, a hybrid approach combining Sugiyama's framework with additive methods (in which each vertex represents a set and the position of the vertex is a sum of vectors representing elements in the set) may be used.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] In this hybrid approach, the vertex permutation and coordinate assignment phases of the algorithm are replaced by a single phase in which the horizontal position of each vertex is chosen as a sum of scalars representing the elements for that vertex.
[src:node-link-diagrams/layered-graph-drawing] Layered graph drawing methods have also been used to provide an initial placement for force-directed graph drawing algorithms.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] A **tree structure**, **tree diagram**, or **tree model** is a way of representing the hierarchical nature of a structure in a graphical form.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] It is named a "tree structure" because the classic representation resembles a tree, although the chart is generally upside down compared to a biological tree, with the "stem" at the top and the "leaves" at the bottom.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] A tree structure is conceptual, and appears in several forms.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] For a discussion of tree structures in specific fields, see Tree (data structure) for computer science; insofar as it relates to graph theory, see tree (graph theory) or tree (set theory).
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Other related articles are listed below.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] The lines connecting elements are called "branches".
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Nodes without children are called leaf nodes, "end-nodes", or "leaves".
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Every finite tree structure has a member that has no superior.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] This member is called the "root" or root node.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] But the converse is not true: infinite tree structures may or may not have a root node.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] The names of relationships between nodes model the kinship terminology of family relations.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] The gender-neutral names "parent" and "child" have largely displaced the older "father" and "son" terminology.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] The term "uncle" is still widely used for other nodes at the same level as the parent, although it is sometimes replaced with gender-neutral terms like "ommer".
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] In the example, "encyclopedia" is the parent of "science" and "culture", its children.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] "Art" and "craft" are siblings, and children of "culture", which is their parent and thus one of their ancestors.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Also, "encyclopedia", as the root of the tree, is the ancestor of "science", "culture", "art" and "craft".
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Finally, "science", "art" and "craft", as leaves, are ancestors of no other node.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] The Oxford English Dictionary records use of both the terms "tree structure" and "tree-diagram" from 1965 in Noam Chomsky's *Aspects of the Theory of Syntax*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] In a tree structure there is one and only one path from any point to any other point.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] For a formal definition see set theory, and for a generalization in which children are not necessarily successors, see prefix order.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] There are many ways of visually representing tree structures.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Layered "icicle" diagrams that use alignment/adjacency.
[src:node-link-diagrams/tree-structure] Lists or diagrams that use indentation, sometimes called "outlines" or "tree views".
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] In a diagram of a graph, a vertex is usually represented by a circle with a label, and an edge is represented by a line or arrow extending from one vertex to another.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] The two vertices forming an edge are said to be the endpoints of this edge, and the edge is said to be incident to the vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A vertex *w* is said to be adjacent to another vertex *v* if the graph contains an edge (*v*,*w*).
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] The neighborhood of a vertex *v* is an induced subgraph of the graph, formed by all vertices adjacent to *v*.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] The degree of a vertex, denoted 𝛿(v) in a graph is the number of edges incident to it.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] An **isolated vertex** is a vertex with degree zero; that is, a vertex that is not an endpoint of any edge (the example image illustrates one isolated vertex).
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A **leaf vertex** (also **pendant vertex**) is a vertex with degree one.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] In a directed graph, one can distinguish the outdegree (number of outgoing edges), denoted 𝛿 +(v), from the indegree (number of incoming edges), denoted 𝛿−(v); a **source vertex** is a vertex with indegree zero, while a **sink vertex** is a vertex with outdegree zero.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A simplicial vertex is one whose closed neighborhood forms a clique: every two neighbors are adjacent.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A universal vertex is a vertex that is adjacent to every other vertex in the graph.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A cut vertex is a vertex the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph; a vertex separator is a collection of vertices the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph into small pieces.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A k-vertex-connected graph is a graph in which removing fewer than *k* vertices always leaves the remaining graph connected.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] An independent set is a set of vertices no two of which are adjacent, and a vertex cover is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of each edge in the graph.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex space of a graph is a vector space having a set of basis vectors corresponding with the graph's vertices.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A graph is vertex-transitive if it has symmetries that map any vertex to any other vertex.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] In the context of graph enumeration and graph isomorphism it is important to distinguish between **labeled vertices** and **unlabeled vertices**.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] A labeled vertex is a vertex that is associated with extra information that enables it to be distinguished from other labeled vertices; two graphs can be considered isomorphic only if the correspondence between their vertices pairs up vertices with equal labels.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] An unlabeled vertex is one that can be substituted for any other vertex based only on its adjacencies in the graph and not based on any additional information.
[src:node-link-diagrams/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex figure of a vertex in a polyhedron is analogous to the neighborhood of a vertex in a graph.
